<section xml:id="sec_geometry-1">
  <title>The Geometry of Complex Numbers, Part I</title>
  <p>
    Complex numbers are ordered pairs of real numbers,
    so they can be represented by points in the plane.
    In this section we show the effect that algebraic operations on complex numbers have on their geometric representations.
  </p>
  <p>
    We can represent the number
    <m>z=x+iy=(x, y)</m> by a position vector in the <m>xy</m> plane whose tail is at the origin and whose head is at the point <m>(x, y)</m>.
    When the <m>xy</m> plane is used for displaying complex numbers,
    it is called the <term>complex plane</term>,
    or more simply, the <term>z plane</term>.
    Recall that <m>\mathrm{Re}(z)=x</m> and <m>\mathrm{Im}(z)=y</m>.
    Geometrically, <m>\mathrm{Re}(z)</m> is the projection of
    <m>z=(x, y)</m> onto the <m>x</m> axis,
    and <m>\mathrm{Im}(z)</m> is the projection of <m>z</m> onto the <m>y</m> axis.
    It makes sense, then,
    to call the <m>x</m> axis the <term>real axis</term>
    and the <m>y</m> axis the <term>imaginary axis</term>,
    as <xref ref="fig_ch-01-07">Figure</xref> illustrates.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-07">
    <caption>The complex plane</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-07.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    Addition of complex numbers is analogous to addition of vectors in the plane.
    As we saw in <xref ref="sec_algebra-1">Section</xref>,
    the sum of <m>z_1=x_1+iy_1=(x_1, y_1)</m> and
    <m>z_2=x_2+iy_2=(x_2, y_2)</m> is <m>(x_1+x_2, y_1+y_2)</m>.
    Hence <m>z_1+z_2</m> can be obtained vectorially by using the
    <q>parallelogram law,</q>
    where the vector sum is the vector represented by the diagonal of the parallelogram formed by the two original vectors.
    <xref ref="fig_ch-01-08">Figure</xref> illustrates this notion.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-08">
    <caption>The sum <m>z_1+z_2</m></caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-08.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The difference <m>z_1-z_2</m> can be represented by the displacement vector from the point
    <m>z_2=(x_2, y_2)</m> to the point <m>z_1=(x_1, y_1)</m>,
    as <xref ref="fig_ch-01-09">Figure</xref> shows.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-09">
    <caption>The difference <m>z_1-z_2</m></caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-09.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <definition xml:id="ModDef">
    <title>Modulus</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>modulus</term>,
        or <term>absolute value</term> <em>,</em>of the complex number <m>z=x+iy</m> is a nonnegative real number denoted by <m>|z|</m> and defined by the relation
        <men xml:id="Modulus">
          |z|=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}
        </men>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    The number <m>|z|</m> is the distance between the origin and the point <m>z=(x, y)</m>.
    The only complex number with modulus zero is the number 0.
    The number <m>z=4+3i</m> has modulus <m>|4+3i| = \sqrt{4^2+3^2}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>,
    and is depicted in <xref ref="fig_ch-01-10">Figure</xref>.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-10">
    <caption>The real and imaginary parts of a complex number</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-10.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The numbers <m>|\mathrm{Re}(z)|, \, |\mathrm{Im}(z)|</m>,
    and <m>|z|</m> are the lengths of the sides of the right triangle <m>OPQ</m> shown in Figure 1.11.
    The inequality <m>|z_1| \lt  |z_2|</m> means that the point <m>z_1</m> is closer to the origin than the point <m>z_2</m>.
    Although obvious from Figure 1.11,
    it is still profitable to work out algebraically
    (which we ask you to do in the exercises)
    that
    <men xml:id="ReImLEMod">
      |x| = |\mathrm{Re}(z)| \le |z|  \text{ and }   |y| = |\mathrm{Im}(z)| \le |z|
    </men>.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-11">
    <caption>The moduli of <m>z</m> and its components</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-11.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The difference <m>z_1-z_2</m> represents the displacement vector from <m>z_2</m> to <m>z_1</m>,
    so the distance between <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> is given by <m>|z_1-z_2|</m>.
    We can obtain this distance by using Definitions (1.2) and <xref ref="ModDef"/> to obtain the familiar formula
    <me>
      \text{ dist } (z_1, z_2) = |z_1-z_2| = \sqrt{(x_1-x_2)^2 + (y_1-y_2)^2}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    If <m>z=(x, y)=x+iy</m>,
    then <m>-z=(-x, -y) = -x-iy</m> is the reflection of <m>z</m> through the origin,
    and <m>\overline{z}=(x, -y) = x-iy</m> is the reflection of <m>z</m> through the <m>x</m> axis,
    as illustrated in <xref ref="fig_ch-01-12">Figure</xref>
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-12">
    <caption>The geometry of negation and conjugation</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-12.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    We can use an important algebraic relationship to establish properties of the absolute value that have geometric applications.
    Its proof is rather straightforward,
    and we ask you to give it in the exercises for this section.
    <men xml:id="ModSq">
      |z|^2 = z\overline{z}
    </men>.
  </p>
  <p>
    An important application of Identity <xref ref="ModSq"/> is its use in establishing the triangle inequality,
    which states that the sum of the lengths of two sides of a triangle is greater than or equal to the length of the third side.
    <xref ref="fig_ch-01-13">Figure</xref> illustrates this inequality.
  </p>
  <theorem>
    <title>The triangle inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> are arbitrary complex numbers, then
        <men xml:id="TriangleIneq">
          |z_1+z_2| \le |z_1| + |z_2|
        </men>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-13">
    <caption>The triangle inequaligy</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-13.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <proof>
    <p>
      We appeal to basic results:
      <md>
        <mrow>|z_1+z_2|^2 \amp = (z_1+z_2) \overline{(z_1+z_2)} \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identity (1.3.3)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (z_1+z_2) (\overline{z_1}+\overline{z_2}) \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identity (1.2.11)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = z_1\overline{z_1} + z_1\overline{z_2} + z_2\overline{z_1} +z_2\overline{z_2} \amp \amp</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = |z_1|^2 + z_1\overline{z_2}+\overline{z_1}z_2 + |z_2|^2 \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identity (1.3.3) and the }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp  \amp \amp  ~\text{ commutative law) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = |z_1|^2 + z_1 \overline{z_2}+\overline{(z_1\overline{z_2})} + |z_2|^2 \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identities (1.2.10) and (1.2.12)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = |z_1|^2 + 2 \mathrm{Re}(z_1 \overline{z_2}) + |z_2|^2 \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identity (1.2.14)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp \le |z_1|^2 + 2|z_1\overline{z_2}| + |z_2|^2 \amp \amp  \text{ (by Identity (1.3.2)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (|z_1| + |z_2|)^2</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Taking square roots yields the desired inequality.
    </p>
  </proof>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        To produce an example of which Figure 1.9 is a reasonable illustration,
        let <m>z_1=7+i</m> and <m>z_2=3+5i</m>.
        Then <m>|z_1| =\sqrt{49+1}=\sqrt{50}</m> and <m>|z_2|=\sqrt{9+25}=\sqrt{34}</m>.
        Clearly, <m>z_1+z_2=10+6i</m>;
        hence <m>|z_1+z_2| =\sqrt{100+36}=\sqrt{136}</m>.
        In this case,
        we can verify the triangle inequality without appealing to calculator approximations because
        <me>
          |z_1+z_2| =\sqrt{136}=2 \sqrt{34}=\sqrt{34}+\sqrt{34}\lt \sqrt{50}+\sqrt{34}=|z_1| + |z_2|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <p>
    We can also establish other important identities by means of the triangle inequality.
    Note that
    <md>
      <mrow>|z_1| \amp = |(z_1+z_2) + (-z_2)|</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp \le |z_1+z_2| + |-z_2|</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = |z_1+z_2| + |z_| </mrow>
    </md>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Subtracting <m>|z_2|</m> from the left and right sides of this string of inequalities gives an important relationship that is used in determining lower bounds of sums of complex numbers:
    <men xml:id="ReverseTriangleIneq">
      |z_1+z_2| \ge |z_1| - |z_2|
    </men>.
  </p>
  <p>
    From Identity <xref ref="ModSq"/> and the commutative and associative laws,
    it follows that
    <me>
      |z_1z_2|^2 = (z_1z_2)\overline{(z_1z_2)} = (z_1\overline{z_1})(z_2\overline{z_2}) = |z_1|^2|z_2|^2
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Taking square roots of the terms on the left and right establishes another important identity:
    <men xml:id="ModProduct">
      |z_1z_2| = |z_1||z_2|
    </men>.
  </p>
  <p>
    As an exercise, we ask you to show that
    <men xml:id="ModQuotient">
      \left|\frac{z_1}{z_2}\right| = \frac{|z_1|}{|z_2|}, \text{ provided }  z_2 \ne 0
    </men>.
  </p>
  <example xml:id="ModProdEx">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>z_1=1+2i</m> and <m>z_2=3+2i</m>,
        then <m>|z_1| = \sqrt{1+4} = \sqrt{5}</m> and <m>|z_2| = \sqrt{9+4} = \sqrt{13}</m>.
        Also <m>z_1z_2=-1+8i</m>;
        hence <m>|z_1z_2| = \sqrt{1+64} = \sqrt{65}= \sqrt{5}\sqrt{13} = |z_1||z_2|</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <p>
    <xref ref="fig_ch-01-14">Figure</xref>
    illustrates the multiplication shown in <xref ref="ModProdEx">Example</xref>.
    The length of the <m>z_1z_2</m> vector apparently equals the product of the lengths of <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>,
    confirming Equation <xref ref="ModProduct"/>,
    but why is it located in the second quadrant when both <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> are in the first quadrant?
    The answer to this question will become apparent to you in <xref ref="sec_geometry-2">Section</xref>.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_ch-01-14">
    <caption>The geometry of multiplication</caption>
    <image width="73%" source="figs/ch-01/ch-01-fig-14.pdf"/>
  </figure>
  <exercises>
    <title>Exercises for <xref ref="sec_geometry-1">Section</xref></title>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_1">
      <p>
        Evaluate the following quantities.
        Put your answer in the form <m>a+ib</m> and show your work.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|(1+i) (2+i)|</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\left|\frac{4-3i}{2-i}\right|</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|(1+i)^{50}| </m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|z\overline{z}|</m>, where <m>z=x+iy</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|z-1|^2</m>, where <m>z=x+iy</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_2">
      <p>
        Plot <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> as vectors,
        then find and plot <m>z_1+z_2</m> and <m>z_1-z_2</m> when
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>z_1=2+3i</m> and <m>z_2=4+i</m>..
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>z_1=-1+2i</m> and <m>z_2=-2+3i</m>..
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>z_1=1+i\sqrt{3}</m> and <m>z_2=-1+i\sqrt{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_3">
      <p>
        Which of the following points lie inside the circle <m>|z-i| =2</m>?
        Explain.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2}+i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sqrt{2}+i(\sqrt{2}+1)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2+3i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{-1}{2}+i\sqrt{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_4">
      <p>
        Prove the following Identities.
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="x1_3_4a">
            <p>
              <xref ref="ReImLEMod"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="x1_3_4b">
            <p>
              <xref ref="ModSq"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="x1_3_4c">
            <p>
              <xref ref="ModQuotient"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_5">
      <p>
        Show that nonzero vectors <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> are perpendicular iff <m>\mathrm{Re}(z_1\overline{z_2})=0</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_14">
      <p>
        Show that nonzero vectors <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> are parallel iff <m>\mathrm{Im}(z_1\overline{z_2})=0</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <p>
        Sketch the sets of points determined by the following relations.\label {1.3.6}
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>|z+1-2i| =2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mathrm{Re}(z+1) =0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>|z+2i| \le 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mathrm{Im}(z-2i) >6</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_7">
      <p>
        Prove that <m>\sqrt{2}|z| \ge |\mathrm{Re}(z)| +|\mathrm{Im}(z)|</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_8">
      <p>
        Show that the point <m>\frac{z_1+z_2}{2}</m> is the midpoint of the line segment joining <m>z_1</m> to <m>z_2</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_9">
      <p>
        Show that <m>|z_1-z_2| \le |z_1| + |z_2|</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_10">
      <p>
        Prove that <m>|z| = 0</m> iff <m>z=0</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_11">
      <p>
        Show that, if <m>z\ne 0</m>, the four points <m>z, \overline{z}, -z</m>,
        and <m>-\overline{z}</m> are the vertices of a rectangle with its center at the origin.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_12">
      <p>
        Show that, if <m>z \ne 0</m>,
        the four points <m>z,\ iz,\ -z</m>,
        and <m>-iz</m> are the vertices of a square with its center at the origin.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_13">
      <p>
        Show that the equation of the line through the points <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> can be expressed in the form <m>z=z_1+t(z_2-z_1)</m>,
        where <m>t</m> is a real number.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_15">
      <p>
        Show that <m>|z_1z_2z_3| = |z_1| |z_2| |z_3|</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_16">
      <p>
        Show that <m>|z^n| = |z|^n</m>,
        where <m>n</m> is an integer.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <p>
        Suppose that either <m>|z| = 1</m> or <m>|w| = 1</m>.
        Prove that <m>|z-w| = |1- \overline{z}w|</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <p>
        Prove the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality:
        <m>|\sum\limits_{k=1}^n z_k w_k|= \sqrt{\sum\limits_{k=1}^n |z_k|^2 \sqrt{\sum\limits_{k=1}^n |w_k|^2}}</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <p>
        Show that <m>\big| |z_1| - |z_2| \big| \le |z_1-z_2|</m>. \label {1.3.17}
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_18">
      <p>
        Show that <m>z_1\overline{z_2} + \overline{z_1}z_2</m> is a real number.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_19">
      <p>
        If you study carefully the proof of the triangle inequality,
        you will note that the reasons for the <em>inequality</em>
        hinge on <m>\mathrm{Re}(z_1 \overline{z_2}) \le |z_1 \overline{z_2}|</m>.
        Under what conditions will these two quantities be equal,
        thus turning the triangle inequality into an equality?
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_20">
      <p>
        Prove that <m>|z_1-z_2|^2 = |z_1|^2 - 2 \mathrm{Re}(z_1 \overline{z_2}) + |z_2|^2</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_21">
      <p>
        Prove by induction that <m>|\sum\limits_{k=1}^n z_k|\le \sum\limits_{k=1}^n |z_k|</m> for all natural numbers <m>n</m>.
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_22">
      <p>
        Let <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> be two distinct points in the complex plane,
        and let <m>K</m> be a positive real constant that is less than the distance between <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that the set of points
              <m>\{z: |z-z_1| - |z-z_2| =K \}</m> is a hyperbola with foci <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the hyperbola with foci <m>\pm 2</m> that goes through the point <m>2+3i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the hyperbola with foci <m>\pm 25</m> that goes through the point <m>7+24i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x1_3_23">
      <p>
        Let <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m> be two distinct points in the complex plane,
        and let <m>K</m> be a positive real constant that is greater than the distance between <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that the set of points
              <m>\{z: |z-z_1| + |z-z_2| =K \}</m> is an ellipse with foci <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the ellipse with foci <m>\pm 3i</m> that goes through the point <m>8-3i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="x1_3_27">
            <p>
              Find the equation of the ellipse with foci <m>\pm 2i</m> that goes through the point <m>3+2i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>